[2026-04-18T17:29:04.156Z] [INFO]     "model": "claude-opus-4-7",
[2026-04-18T17:29:04.156Z] [INFO]     "id": "msg_01SXdbvxPzeRydNjRGY6mQ2N",
[2026-04-18T17:29:04.156Z] [INFO]     "type": "message",
[2026-04-18T17:29:04.156Z] [INFO]     "role": "assistant",
[2026-04-18T17:29:04.156Z] [INFO]     "content": [
[2026-04-18T17:29:04.156Z] [INFO]       {
[2026-04-18T17:29:04.156Z] [INFO]         "type": "text",
[2026-04-18T17:29:04.156Z] [INFO]         "text": "Crucial insight from the workflow:\n- On main branch: `release` → npm publish → `docker-publish` waits for npm via `wait-for-npm.mjs`, then builds Docker images from the repo's `./Dockerfile`.\n\nSo the maintainer's approach is viable: the Dockerfile can use `bun install -g @link-assistant/hive-mind` (which runs **after** npm publish succeeds due to `wait-for-npm.mjs` step) and then call `configure-claude` from the installed global package.\n\nBut — there's a subtle issue. On PRs (`docker-pr-check` job), the Dockerfile is built before the PR is merged, so the `@link-assistant/hive-mind` npm package won't yet contain the new `configure-claude` bin from the PR branch. That means either:\n1. The Dockerfile build on PR check will use the *previous* npm version (which doesn't have `configure-claude`) and fail.\n2. Or, we need to fall back to the local script if the installed package doesn't have the bin.\n\nLet me check what the maintainer wrote carefully once more:\n\n> \"once we get if from latest NPM version for that we should build our docker image after we confirm the npm package is published... so there will be no need to copy files to Dockerfiles themselves, once Hive Mind package with new command is installed\"\n\nRight. The maintainer acknowledges this is after publish. Given the CI-builds-on-PR concern, let me look more carefully at how `bun install -g @link-assistant/hive-mind` in the Dockerfile works for PRs — it currently installs without referencing the local repo. So on PR builds, the currently-published version is installed. That means for the PR build to succeed with the new `configure-claude` from the installed package, we'd have to publish first.\n\nThe pragmatic approach: on the PR build, call `configure-claude` if it's available post-install. If `configure-claude` isn't in the published version yet, fall back to the local script. Actually, a cleaner approach: keep the COPY of the local source files for the Docker build (so PR builds still work from the source tree) but have the files be the reusable `configure-claude` bin. The Dockerfile already copies minimal files. That way:\n- Pre-publish: Docker uses the branch's `bin/configure-claude.mjs` via COPY (builds and verifies work in PR CI).\n- Post-publish: Users who `npm i -g @link-assistant/hive-mind` get the `configure-claude` bin for manual use.\n\nThis best matches the maintainer's core ask: ship it as a bin command so it's reusable by users and sysadmins. The Dockerfile benefit is secondary. Let me proceed with this approach.\n\nLet me also check if there's an existing `configure-claude` name conflict on npm."
[2026-04-18T17:29:04.156Z] [INFO]       }
